Slavic Greek Latin Academy
It is only possible to reconstruct the educational process, the educational programme and the teaching methods used at the Slavic Greek Latin Academy with an integrated study of the surviving sources. A comparative study of the teaching process and educational programmes of higher schools in Western Europe and the Christian East is also important, because the Likhud Brothers apparently taught following the tradition they had experienced as students at Greek schools and at the University of Padua. This approach is justified by the fact that no direct sources containing the necessary information are available. The distribution of subjects by classes and years of education was of a most general character. The basic principle of teaching was the gradual presentation of information. The Academy was divided into two parts. The first – initial or preparatory – part was the Slavic department, preparing the students for subsequent levels of study. Starostas (elders), who were students of the senior classes of the Academy, taught at the Slavic school at the same time. As new students entered and the “old” ones progressed, the number of forms increased at the Academy. From 1690 onwards, the school was divided into five forms. It is difficult to determine accurately how long it took for students to master one subject, although according to our findings we can conclude that most often students spent from one to two years in a form. As a rule, the fifth (or fourth, depending on the year) form (class) was the lowest one. In the lowest class, students studied “verbal Greek”, which apparently included the study of Greek speaking and reading. This allowed students to communicate with their Greek teachers and to cope with subsequent courses in Greek. The Greek Dionisy (Dionysius), a student in the first class of the Academy, taught the class (RGADA, f. 1182, op. 1, d. 96, fol. 53v). The fourth-class students studied “small grammar composition” (ibid., fol. 53) whereas “big grammar composition” was studied in the third class (ibid., fol. 52). Grammar was taught with the already well-known grammar book by Constantine Lascaris, as well as with the Likhuds’ own textbooks. In all likelihood, the “small grammar composition” and the “big grammar composition” mentioned in the Book Printing Prikaz documents correspond to their books Short Grammar and Extensive Grammar. According to the title of the Likhuds’ extensive grammar book (“Грамматика обращенная к школе риторики” (“Grammar Book Addressed to the Rhetoric School”)), it corresponded to a preparatory course undertaken just before studying rhetoric. The teaching of grammar was accompanied by the teaching of poetics and epistolography. Apparently, the teaching of all the subjects was completed in the second class of the Academy. The grammar, poetics and epistolography courses were followed by a course of rhetoric. In its turn, it was followed by a course of logic, which began to be taught only in 1690. A course in physics or natural philosophy followed afterwards. For grammar and poetics, the Likhud brothers taught only in Greek. Rhetoric, logic and physics were taught in both Greek and Latin.
At the Slavic Greek Latin Academy, students participated in debates on the material learnt. The debates took place on Sundays and Feast days. “Teachings or explanations of the Biblical Stories” were taught to the students (<i>Сменцовский М.Н.</i> Братья Лихуды..., p. 79). The students showed their achievements to the patriarch and to tsars for Easter and for Christmas (RGADA, f. 235, op. 2, d. 128, fol. 139). The higher educational institutions of Western Europe undoubtedly influenced the construction of the educational process and the ways disciplines were taught and information was presented. It is also obvious that it was impossible to automatically copy and transfer everything to Russia, therefore it was important to adapt the educational process and material established at European universities to the Russian reality.
At the Italian School, in 1697–1700, the teaching of Italian was based on the same order in the presentation of the material. The language course was supposed to begin with the alphabet and the basics of the language, including reading. The acquisition of writing skills could not take place without accomplishing tasks in grammar and in writing various compositions on given topics. And the last stage was apparently focused on oral presentations by students. Apparently, learning to speak was one of the most difficult tasks for students, because the documents often mention their low level in speaking, which was the last component to be completed (“they speak poorly”, “have been taught too little to speak”), while the same students were usually able to read and write. However, it should be noted that in this case the “ability to write” apparently meant the simplest knowledge of morphology and spelling, while complex constructions were only studied at the end of the second year of education. In autumn 1699, in the Likhud brothers’ reports, there appeared a new criterion characterising the level of knowledge of the students at the school: by the time they had learned not only to “read and write in Italian and to speak well”, they were “already at the end of the big grammar syntax” (RGADA, f. 210, op. 9, col. 773, st. 3, fol. 134-135).
Novgorod School of the Likhud Brothers. Historiography has repeatedly noted that the level and system of teaching at the Novgorod School was very similar to the Slavic Greek Latin Academy with one exception: it did not offer philosophy courses, because these were supposed to be taught only in higher educational institutions. In addition, there are two concepts as to how Greek was taught at the Novgorod School. In the first case, the teaching of subjects is believed to have been conducted in Greek and Slavonic, where Greek was the studied language, and where Slavonic was the meta-language (Strakhova O.B.). The other hypothesis suggests that simple Greek could have been used as a meta-language (D.A. Yalamas). So far, some of the texts from the Likhud brothers’ textbooks have been available in two versions, both with parallel Slavonic translations and without them; hence the coexistence of the two methods is possible.
Some subjects were taught at the Novgorod School according to the textbooks that Ioanniky Likhud had written specially. A book called “Rhetoric” was among them; its list was preserved in the collection of the Novgorod Theological Seminary (RNB (National Library of Russia)). Probably, the creation of the textbook was also part of the educational process, because the manuscript was written by students of the school, and the text was then corrected by the teacher.

Slavic Greek Latin Academy. The formation of the teaching system and the introduction of new academic disciplines in the educational process presupposed the availability and use of a number of textbooks. The issue of providing students with relevant educational literature was one of the most challenging. First of all, Ioanniky and his brother compiled their own textbooks, because the introduction of nearly every new course depended on the availability of the corresponding textbook. The first textbook was Grammar (the so-called “Short Grammar” – in the copies: RGB (Russian State Library) OR (Manuscript Department), f. 173, “fund”, No. 331, 333; Patmos, Monastery of St. John the Theologian, No. 838; RGIA (Russian State Historical Archives), f. 834, op. 3, No. 3376). A simultaneous study of grammar and poetics is proved not only by general ideas about teaching at schools of the time, but also by surviving manuscripts of Likhuds’ textbooks, where the Short Grammar is accompanied by a course in poetics (RGB, OR, f. 173, “fund”, No. 331, 333; BANU OR, No. 337 p). In addition, manuscript copies of Greek and Latin grammar books are available (Mount Athos, Iviron, No. 202).
The second educational course that accompanied the study of grammar was devoted to epistolography, and this was according to the tradition of the Greek schools. Among the surviving works there is an epistolography textbook (RNB, Greek 504); the Likhud Brothers’ letters are also available, which, in all likelihood, could in some part represent manuals for teaching the discipline. 
Then rhetoric was taught. In the late 17th century, Sofrony wrote a textbook on rhetoric for the Slavic Greek Latin Academy. It was a textbook in Greek. Nine Greek manuscript copies which are still available show how much the book was in demand in the 18th century: GIM (State Historical Museum), Uvar. 214; RNB (National Library of Russia), Greek No. 506, Greek 706, SpbDA (Saint Petersburg Theological Academy), B.II.10; BAN (Library of the Russian Academy of Sciences), Q No. 3; NBKhU. No. 54 (25); EVE, No. 3232; Mount Athos. Iviron, No. 108; KKh(P)FU, NB, Inv. No. 4376.
As for the teaching of logic, the textbooks on these disciplines are represented by the codes OR RGB, f. 173, No. 299, 300.
The manuscript of the “Introduction to Physics” (NIOR RGB, f. 173(I) MDA, No. 301) was written by Sofrony and is “a copy of interpretations of Aristotle’s "Physics" by Gerasim Vlach (Vlakh), who corresponded with Sofrony Likhud for several months in 1669” (about this: <i>Фонкич</i><i> </i><i>Б</i><i>.</i><i>Л</i><i>.</i> Новые материалы для биографии Лихудов... p. 71) The code dates from 1669 and consists of ten parts.
Nonetheless, handwritten textbooks were not sufficient, so a number of printed materials, necessary for the educational process, were acquired. Among the account books of the Patriarchal Treasury Prikaz, there is a record dated 19 November 1687, concerning the acquisition of books and their transfer by “the Greek teacher hieromonk to Ioaniky and Sofrony for the new stone schools that are built in the Spassky Monastery, which is behind the icon stand, for the teachings of the disciples” (RGADA, f. 235, op. 2, d. 127, fol. 158v). The document lists all the books purchased.
