Sofrony Likhud’s (Sophronios Leichoudes) Moscow Greek School. The school programme consisted of Greek grammar, rhetoric, poetics and logic. The subjects were taught gradually in accordance with the level of knowledge of the student. The lowest level of education, “soliturgics”, presented the basics of Greek reading and writing. Then the order was as follows: the Octoechos, the Book of Psalms, Greek grammar. Composition or syntax, where syntax was studied, was the next level of learning. After studying grammar, they studied rhetoric, and then logic.
Copying texts and translating was a common practice in language studies both at the Slavic Greek Latin Academy and in the Greek schools in Novgorod and Moscow. Therefore, these schools can be regarded as centres of book-writing and translation activities of the day.

Slavic Greek Latin Academy. The formation of the teaching system and the introduction of new academic disciplines in the educational process presupposed the availability and use of a number of textbooks. The issue of providing students with relevant educational literature was one of the most challenging. First of all, Sofrony and his brother compiled their own textbooks, because the introduction of nearly every new course depended on the availability of the corresponding textbook. The first textbook was Grammar (the so-called “Short Grammar” – in the copies: NIOR RGB, f. 173, “fund”, No. 331, 333; Patmos, Monastery of St. John the Theologian, No. 838; RGIA, f. 834, op. 3, No. 3376.). A simultaneous study of grammar and poetics is proved not only by general ideas about teaching at schools of that time, but also by surviving manuscripts of Likhuds’ textbooks, where the Short Grammar is accompanied by a course in poetics (NIOR RGB, f. 173, “fund”, No. 331, 333; BANU OR, No. 337 p). In addition, manuscript copies of Greek and Latin grammars are available (Mount Athos, Iviron, No. 202).
The second educational course that accompanied the study of grammar was devoted to the epistolography, and this was according to the tradition of the Greek schools. Among the surviving works there is an epistolography textbook (RNB, Greek 504); the Likhud Brothers’ letters are also available, which, in all likelihood, could in some part represent manuals for teaching the discipline. 
Then rhetoric was taught. In the late 17th century, Sofrony wrote a textbook on rhetoric for the Slavic Greek Latin Academy. It was a textbook in Greek. Nine Greek lists that are still available show how much the book was in demand in the 18th century: GIM.Uvar.214; RNB, Greek No. 506, Greek 706, SpbDA (Saint Petersburg Theological Academy), B.II.10; BAN (Library of the Russian Academy of Sciences), Q No. 3; NBKhU. No. 54 (25); EVE, No. 3323; Mount Athos, Iviron, No. 108; KKh(P)FU, NB, Inv. No. 4376.
As for the teaching of logic, the textbooks on these disciplines are represented by the codes OR RGB, f. 173, No. 299, 300 and were the fair and draft copies of Sofrony Likhud’s work on “Logic”. The manuscripts were written in Greek (autograph by Sofrony Likhud). Part of the textbook was written in Padua in 1669. Copy No. 299 was made at the end of the 17th century. Part of copy No. 300 was made in 1690–1691. The “Logic” by Sofrony Likhud consists of four parts: 1) Logic in three books; 2) Introduction to Aristotle’s “Logic”; 3) Presentation and analysis of the “Introduction to Aristotle’s Categories” by Porphyry; 4) Presentation and analysis of Aristotle’s “Categories”.
The manuscript of the “Introduction to Physics” (NIOR RGB, f. 173(I) MDA, No. 301) was written by Sofrony and is “a copy of interpretations of Aristotle’s "Physics" by Gerasim Vlach (Vlakh), who corresponded with Sofrony Likhud for several months in 1669” (about this: <i>Фонкич</i><i> </i><i>Б</i><i>.</i><i>Л</i><i>.</i> Новые материалы для биографии Лихудов... p. 71) The code dates from 1669 and consists of ten parts.
Nonetheless, handwritten textbooks were not sufficient, so a number of printed materials, necessary for the educational process, were acquired. Among the account books of the Patriarchal Treasury Prikaz, there is a record dated November 19, 1687 concerning the acquisition of books and their transfer by “the Greek teacher hieromonk to Ioaniky and Sofrony for the new stone schools that are built in the Spassky Monastery, which is behind the icon stand, for the teachings of the disciples” (RGADA, f. 235, op. 2, d. 127, fol. 158v). The document lists all the books purchased.
