In total, according to the list, 132 books were bought. In fact, all of them were intended for studying and were typical of the libraries of higher educational institutions in Western Europe and Greece in the 15th – 18th centuries. Almost all the editions from the list are identifiable, and some individual copies of the books mentioned in the document have survived to the present day. For example, Vlach (Vlakh)’s lexicon mentioned first in the list is a four-language lexicon that was completed by Gerasim Vlakh in Venice and published there in 1659 (<i>Legrand É.</i> Bibliographie Hellénique ou description raisonnée des ouvrages publiés par des Grecs au XVIIe siècle, T. 2. Paris, 1903, p. 115, No. 434). Several copies of the work that were undoubtedly used at the Academy are still available (on this: <i>Ховрина</i><i> </i><i>Т</i><i>.</i><i>К</i><i>.</i> «Четырехъязычный тезаурус Герасима Влаха в переводе справщиков Московского Печатного двора» // Россия и Христианский Восток, iss. 4–5. Moscow, 2014, p.; <i>Рамазанова Д.Н.</i> «Четырехъязычный Лексикон» Герасима Влаха 1659 г. Новые материалы // Книга. Исследования и материалы. сб. 88: 2 parts, pt. 2, Moscow, 2008. pp. 175-185). The title “Армонии Влаховы” represents the work by G. Vlach (Vlakh), published in Venice in 1661 (<i>Legrand</i><i> É. </i>Bibliographie Hellénique … T. 2, pp. 136-139, No. 443). 
Among other books, the record lists the necessary textbooks on rhetoric as well as printed Greek grammar books. Among the books purchased, two textbooks on Greek, basic for the 15th – 16th centuries, also appear in the list. These are the Grammar book by the Greek scholar of the 15th century Theodorus Gaza (Theodore Gazis) (Theodori Gazae Grammaticae introductionis libri quatuor… Venice, 1545), and the Grammar book by Constantine Lascaris (Γραμματική... / νεωστί μετατυπωθείσα, και μετά πλείστης επιμελείας διορθωθείσα παρά του κοινού βιβλιοφύλακος Γραδενίγου της των Ενετών αριστοκρατείας… Ενετίησιν: τυπ. Γλυκύς, Νικόλαος (ο εξ Ιωαννίνων), 1673), created in the 2nd half of the 15th century.
The Italian School. The available sources do not present any information concerning the textbooks the Likhud Brothers used to teach Italian; there is only evidence of a certain book by Lemertan/Lementar. The list made for Protopopov’s son Ivan Ivanov, sent to the Likhud Brothers to study Italian, informs us that “he went for studying and his teachers did not give him Lemartar’s books” (f. 210, op. 9, col. 773, st. 3, fol. 116-116v). However, it would be more correct to assume that the word “lemertan” meant the Italian word elementare (simple, elementary) in the Russian transcription, which was a usual term for the name of alphabet books and elementary grammar textbooks in various European languages. Thus, what is meant here is a textbook containing the Italian alphabet or a basic grammar. The textbooks were at the disposal of the Likhud Brothers, because the Order-in-Charge Prikaz, investigating the case of Ivan Ivanov’s son Protopopov, discovered that “they (the Likhud Brothers) would give him the Lementar for learning, either for a price or without money” (ibid.). However, the Italian grammar course (especially syntax) could not be based only on an elementary grammar textbook. Later other textbooks, including a full course of the Italian language, were to be involved. It is known that by the end of the 17th century, there was a large choice of textbooks on the Italian language, the grammatical tradition of which had begun to develop at the beginning of the 16th century.
Sofrony Likhud’s Moscow Greek School used the same textbooks for the Greek language compiled by the Likhud Brothers, as well as the same authors and texts that were used for teaching at the Slavic Greek Latin Academy and at the Novgorod School.

