Students and their social status:
Nobility; perhaps merchants.
The Uvarov family: 
Darya Ivanovna, born Golovina (before 1766 – not earlier than 1820), widow of Semyon (Semen) Uvarov (1743–1788), vice-colonel of the Leib-Grenadier Regiment; mother of Sergey Uvarov;
Sergey Semyonovich (Semenovich) Uvarov (1786–1855): from 1846 onwards, he was a count, a major statesman and minister of National (Public) Education (1833–1848);
Fyodor (Fedor) Semyonovich (Semenovich) Uvarov (1787–1845), brother of Sergey Uvarov, later a major-general and commander of the Ekaterinoslav Cuirassier Regiment.
The Kurakin family:
Princess Natalya Ivanovna, born Golovina (1766–1831), Sergey Uvarov’s aunt, a statsdame (lady of the suite), an amateur composer and musician;
Prince Aleksey (Alexei) Borisovich (1759–1829), an actual privy councillor and prosecutor-general at the Governing Senate (1796–1798).
Their children:
Boris Kurakin (1783–1850), later a chamberlain and senator;
Elena Kurakina (1787–1869), later a musician, married to Count N.I. Zotov (1782–1849); Claire Clairmont worked in their family as a governess;
Alexandra Kurakina (1788–1819), later married to N.S. Saltykov (1786–1849), but left him for P.A. Chicherin (1778–1848).

